---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="A Year in Your Own Data Build-a-thon | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="A build-a-thon where the dataset is you — turn a year of your own data into a visualization worth keeping."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                Upcoming: A Year in Your Own Data — A Build-a-thon
            </h2>

            <div class="mb-6 text-gray-700">
                <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
                    Saturday, Jul 25 · 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM CDT
                </p>
                <p class="flex items-start gap-2 mt-1">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-gray-400"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="currentColor"
                        aria-hidden="true"
                    >
                        <path
                            fill-rule="evenodd"
                            d="M12 2c-3.866 0-7 3.07-7 6.857 0 4.34 4.686 9.86 6.412 11.74a.8.8 0 0 0 1.176 0C14.314 18.717 19 13.197 19 8.857 19 5.07 15.866 2 12 2Zm0 9.5a2.5 2.5 0 1 1 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 1 0 5Z"
                            clip-rule="evenodd"></path>
                    </svg>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >The Coffee Shop NE</span
                        ><br />2852 Johnson St NE · Minneapolis, MN</span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                You've been collecting data all year. Let's make something out
                of it.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Join <span class="font-silkscreen">tcplot</span> for a build-a-thon
                where the dataset is <em>you</em>. Bring a year of your own data
                — steps, sleep, songs, spending, miles, messages, books, photos
                — and spend the session turning it into a visualization worth
                keeping. Code it, draw it, or build it by hand.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                The best personal-data projects aren't about the numbers;
                they're about the story only you can tell. A year is long enough
                to hold a season, a habit, a heartbreak, a move. We'll help you
                find the one thread worth pulling.
            </p>

            <!-- ===== Example viz: one person's YouTube Music library ===== -->
            <section
                class="my-12"
                style="font-family: Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;"
            >
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                    An example, built from one person's data
                </h3>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                    Here's one I made from a <strong class="text-gray-900"
                        >Google Takeout</strong
                    > export — a whole YouTube Music library, 6,497 songs by 1,473
                    artists, listed A→Z. Each bar is an artist; its length and color
                    show how many songs are by them (<span
                        class="font-semibold"
                        style="color:#d6263a">red = the most</span
                    >,
                    <span class="font-semibold" style="color:#7b3fb0"
                        >violet = the fewest</span
                    >). Press play and turn your sound on: one steady beat per
                    artist, and the <em>pitch</em> is mapped to the count just like
                    the color — a run of one-song artists ticks along at the same
                    low pitch, and the pitch jumps up when an artist has more songs.
                    Or grab the list (or the handle on the right) and drag to scrub
                    the play position anywhere in the A→Z.
                </p>

                <div
                    class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white shadow-sm overflow-hidden"
                >
                    <div
                        class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 px-4 py-3 border-b border-gray-100 bg-gray-50"
                    >
                        <button
                            id="yiyd-play"
                            class="px-4 py-1.5 rounded-md bg-gray-900 text-white text-sm font-medium hover:bg-gray-700 transition"
                            >Play ▶</button
                        >
                        <button
                            id="yiyd-restart"
                            class="px-3 py-1.5 rounded-md bg-white border border-gray-300 text-gray-700 text-sm hover:bg-gray-100 transition"
                            >Restart</button
                        >
                        <span class="mx-1 text-gray-300">|</span>
                        <span class="text-sm text-gray-500">Speed:</span>
                        <button
                            id="yiyd-sp-1"
                            data-active="true"
                            class="yiyd-sp px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-white border border-gray-300 text-gray-700 text-sm hover:bg-gray-100 data-[active=true]:bg-gray-900 data-[active=true]:text-white data-[active=true]:border-gray-900 transition"
                            >1×</button
                        >
                        <button
                            id="yiyd-sp-2"
                            class="yiyd-sp px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-white border border-gray-300 text-gray-700 text-sm hover:bg-gray-100 data-[active=true]:bg-gray-900 data-[active=true]:text-white data-[active=true]:border-gray-900 transition"
                            >2×</button
                        >
                        <button
                            id="yiyd-sp-3"
                            class="yiyd-sp px-2.5 py-1 rounded-md bg-white border border-gray-300 text-gray-700 text-sm hover:bg-gray-100 data-[active=true]:bg-gray-900 data-[active=true]:text-white data-[active=true]:border-gray-900 transition"
                            >4×</button
                        >
                        <span class="ml-auto text-xs text-gray-400"
                            >🔊 sound on</span
                        >
                    </div>
                    <div id="yiyd-canvas" class="w-full"></div>
                </div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mt-2">
                    Built with p5.js from a <strong class="text-gray-500"
                        >Google Takeout</strong
                    > export — the exact same kind of personal data you'll bring and
                    work with at the build-a-thon. The same dataset could just as
                    easily be a map, a calendar, or a string of beads.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- p5 + sketch (loaded inline, in document order) -->
            <script
                is:inline
                src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/p5@1.9.4/lib/p5.min.js"
            ></script>
            <script
                is:inline
                src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/p5@1.9.4/lib/addons/p5.sound.min.js"
            ></script>
            <script is:inline src="/yiyd-music-sketch.js"></script>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What you'll do
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Bring — or pull on the spot — a year of your own
                        personal data</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Pick the one question you actually want it to answer</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Build a visualization — interactive, static, or
                        physical — solo or in a small group</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span>Share what you made and what it told you</span>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Where to find a year of your data
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Most of it is already sitting in an app, waiting for an export.
                A few places to look:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong class="text-gray-900">Health apps</strong> — Apple
                        Health, Google Fit, or Fitbit export steps, sleep, and workouts
                        day by day.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong class="text-gray-900">Music</strong> — request your
                        <a
                            href="https://www.spotify.com/us/account/privacy/"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Spotify streaming history</a
                        >: every track you played, with timestamps.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong class="text-gray-900">Google Takeout</strong> — export
                        your <a
                            href="https://takeout.google.com/"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">data</a
                        >: location history, photos metadata, search, YouTube,
                        and more.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong class="text-gray-900">Money</strong> — download a
                        year of transactions from your bank or card and tally spending
                        by category.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong class="text-gray-900">Movement & media</strong>
                        — Strava and Garmin for runs and rides; Letterboxd and Goodreads
                        for films and books.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong class="text-gray-900">Screen time</strong> — iOS
                        Screen Time or Android Digital Wellbeing for how the hours
                        actually went.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-base text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">
                Some exports take a day or two to arrive, so request yours
                before the event. Your data stays yours — bring only what you're
                comfortable working with in a room of friendly people.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What to bring
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Your laptop and charger, a year of your data (or be ready to
                download it), and whatever tools you love — D3, Tableau,
                ggplot2, Observable, a spreadsheet, or just paper and beads. No
                tools at all is fine too.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Who this is for
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Anyone curious about their own life in data — seasoned coders
                and total beginners alike. Come build something only you could
                make.
            </p>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                Hope to see you there!
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
